{"summary":{"verdict":"BLOCK","one_liner":"Timezone-blind cutoff check will approve/reject orders incorrectly for every non-UTC customer — guaranteed production failures."},"critical_findings":[{"title":"getHours() uses server timezone (UTC), not customer local time","risk":"A New York customer placing an order at 12:00 noon EST (17:00 UTC) will be denied same-day delivery because getHours() returns 17, which is >= 14. Conversely, a London customer ordering at 14:30 BST (13:30 UTC) in summer will be incorrectly approved because getHours() returns 13. Every order outside UTC is evaluated against the wrong clock.","severity":"Critical","location":"isSameDayDeliveryAvailable() — `orderTime.getHours()` call","reproduction":"1. Server runs in UTC. 2. New York customer orders at 12:00 noon local (EST, UTC-5). 3. `orderTime` is `2026-03-20T17:00:00Z`. 4. `getHours()` returns 17. 5. Function returns false — customer is wrongly denied same-day delivery despite ordering 2 hours before their local cutoff.","fix":"Accept the customer's IANA timezone as a parameter and resolve the local hour explicitly. Example using Temporal (Stage 3) or a library like date-fns-tz:

```typescript
function isSameDayDeliveryAvailable(
  orderTime: Date,
  customerTimezone: string // e.g. 'America/New_York', 'Europe/London'
): boolean {
  const cutoffHour = 14;
  const formatter = new Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', {
    hour: 'numeric',
    hour12: false,
    timeZone: customerTimezone,
  });
  const localHour = parseInt(formatter.format(orderTime), 10);
  return localHour < cutoffHour;
}
```","time_to_fix":"30 minutes","acceptance_criteria_affected":"Same-day delivery must respect the customer's local 14:00 cutoff regardless of server timezone or customer location."},{"title":"No DST transition handling — ambiguous/skipped hours cause wrong decisions","risk":"During spring-forward (e.g., London clocks jump 01:00→02:00 on last Sunday of March), the local hour 01:00–01:59 is skipped. During fall-back, 01:00–01:59 occurs twice. If the cutoff were near a transition boundary, or if the server itself observes DST (common misconfiguration), getHours() can return an hour that doesn't correspond to any real local time, silently approving or rejecting orders. Even with the timezone fix above, a naive offset calculation (UTC ± N) rather than IANA-based resolution will break across DST transitions.","severity":"High","location":"isSameDayDeliveryAvailable() — implicit UTC assumption","reproduction":"1. Set server TZ to Europe/London (ops misconfiguration). 2. On 2026-03-29 (UK spring-forward), at 00:30 UTC the server clock jumps to 01:30 BST. 3. An order timestamped 00:45 UTC could report getHours() as 1 (BST), shifting the effective cutoff by one hour. 4. Similar drift for any hardcoded UTC±N offset approach.","fix":"Always use IANA timezone identifiers (e.g., 'Europe/London', 'America/New_York') with Intl.DateTimeFormat or a TZ library — never compute offsets manually. The Intl API handles DST transitions automatically.","time_to_fix":"0 minutes if the IANA-based fix from finding #1 is adopted (it already handles this). If a manual offset approach is chosen instead, add ~1 hour for DST lookup logic and edge-case tests.","acceptance_criteria_affected":"Cutoff must be correct year-round, including across DST transitions."},{"title":"No input validation — invalid or undefined Date silently returns incorrect result","risk":"If `orderTime` is `undefined`, `null`, or an invalid Date (`new Date('garbage')`), `getHours()` returns `NaN`. `NaN < 14` evaluates to `false`, silently denying same-day delivery with no error logged. In a backend service receiving deserialized JSON, this is a realistic scenario (missing field, malformed ISO string).","severity":"High","location":"isSameDayDeliveryAvailable() — no guard on `orderTime`","reproduction":"1. Call `isSameDayDeliveryAvailable(new Date('not-a-date'))`. 2. `getHours()` returns `NaN`. 3. `NaN < 14` → `false`. 4. Customer silently denied same-day delivery; no error thrown or logged.","fix":"```typescript
if (!(orderTime instanceof Date) || isNaN(orderTime.getTime())) {
  throw new Error(`Invalid orderTime: ${orderTime}`);
}
```","time_to_fix":"5 minutes","acceptance_criteria_affected":"System must fail visibly on bad input rather than silently degrading the customer experience."}],"important_issues":[{"title":"Cutoff hour is hardcoded — no per-region configurability","description":"London and New York may need different cutoff hours based on local logistics capacity. A single hardcoded `14` doesn't allow for this. Consider a config map keyed by timezone/region.","location":"const cutoffHour = 14"},{"title":"Midnight boundary not considered","description":"If a customer's local time is e.g. 00:30 (after midnight), `getHours()` returns 0 which is < 14, so the function returns true. But depending on business rules, an order placed at 00:30 may belong to the *previous* calendar day's delivery window, not the current day's. The function doesn't reason about which calendar day the delivery is for.","location":"isSameDayDeliveryAvailable() — return statement"}],"suggestions":["Add unit tests for each supported timezone at boundary hours (13:59 local, 14:00 local, 14:01 local) and across DST transition dates.","Consider using a per-region cutoff configuration rather than a global constant, since logistics networks in different cities have different fulfillment windows.","Log when same-day delivery is denied so customer support can diagnose complaints — currently this is a silent boolean with no audit trail."],"production_readiness":{"deployment_risks":"Every non-UTC customer is currently getting wrong same-day delivery decisions. Deploying the platform expansion to New York without fixing this will systematically deny valid orders or approve invalid ones.","rollback_capability":"N/A — this is a logic bug in a pure function, not a deployment artifact. Rollback doesn't apply; the code needs a fix.","backward_compatibility":"Adding a `customerTimezone` parameter is a breaking change to the function signature. All callers must be updated to pass timezone. This is necessary and non-negotiable — the current interface is fundamentally broken.","monitoring_coverage":"No monitoring exists. Add metrics for same-day eligibility decisions broken down by customer timezone to detect drift.","breaking_changes":{"api_breaking":true,"db_destructive":false,"shared_library":false,"auth_security":false,"data_pipeline":false,"config_changes":true,"details":["Function signature must change to accept customerTimezone — all callers need updating","Cutoff configuration should move to per-region config"]},"safe_to_deploy":false,"rollback_plan":"N/A — do not deploy to New York market until timezone handling is fixed. Current London behavior is also incorrect during BST (summer)."},"escalations":[],"confidence":{"level":97,"high_confidence_areas":["Timezone bug is deterministic and provable — getHours() on a UTC server cannot return local time for non-UTC customers","Invalid Date producing NaN is standard JS behavior, trivially reproducible","DST transition risk is well-documented for manual offset approaches"],"low_confidence_areas":["Business rules around midnight-boundary orders — may or may not be a real issue depending on product requirements"],"assumptions":["Server runs in UTC as stated","orderTime is constructed from client-submitted or API-received timestamps","The 14:00 cutoff is meant to apply in the customer's local timezone, not UTC"]}}
